      The magical Elon money machineSo obviously  this is a story about  El=
on Musk=E2=80=99s=C2=A0magic lamp that makes the price of Bitcoin go up and=
 down:Bitcoin traded lower on Tuesday as prices pulled back from a double-d=
igit percentage rally, stoked in part by Elon Musk=E2=80=99s effort to bols=
ter the token=E2=80=99s green credentials on Twitter.The largest digital cu=
rrency slipped as much as 6.5% to $36,494 in New York, following a 16% jump=
 on Monday. The wider Bloomberg Galaxy Crypto Index and tokens including Et=
her also dropped.The Tesla Inc. CEO has roiled the token=E2=80=99s price th=
is month, triggering a selloff by criticizing its energy profile and suspen=
ding Bitcoin payments. Heightened regulatory rhetoric on cryptocurrencies f=
rom China also pressured the sector.=E2=80=9CIf the market continues to see=
 wild swings based on Elon Musk tweets, it=E2=80=99s going to be a big set =
back for this asset class,=E2=80=9D said Matt Maley, chief market strategis=
t for=C2=A0Miller Tabak + Co.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe fact that it sees such wild=
 swings to the tweets from one person takes away the legitimacy of the asse=
t class.=E2=80=9DFine, yes, in 2021 the main fact about Bitcoin is that Elo=
n Musk decides whether its price goes up or down. Does that =E2=80=9Ctake a=
way the legitimacy of the asset class=E2=80=9D? Man, look around; =E2=80=9C=
legitimacy=E2=80=9D is a weird thing to be worried about. I would say that =
it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0interesting=C2=A0to have a trillion-dollar asset class th=
at is like =E2=80=9Cone guy will think of a number and your asset will be w=
orth that number.=E2=80=9D That really is a novel experiment in finance! I =
feel like we should give it some more time and see how it goes.=C2=A0But it=
 strikes me that this is also a story about how environmental, social and g=
overnance (ESG) investing often works. In 2021 the other important fact abo=
ut Bitcoin is that  miners use a lot of electricity to keep its ledger secu=
re, and this fact has formed the pretext for a number of Musk=E2=80=99s rec=
ent tweets telling the price to go up or down:Pledges to make the industry =
more green have picked up since Musk=E2=80=99s criticisms. Several miners j=
oined the Crypto Climate Accord, a private-sector initiative to decarbonize=
 the crypto industry by 2030.Musk and Michael Saylor, another long-time Bit=
coin booster, tweeted Monday that they had held a call with major North Ame=
rican miners, including Michael Novogratz=E2=80=99s Galaxy Digital and publ=
icly traded Hut 8 Mining Corp., to discuss =E2=80=9Cenergy usage transparen=
cy.=E2=80=9DSaylor said the group agreed to form the Bitcoin Mining Council=
 =E2=80=9Cto standardize energy reporting.=E2=80=9DMusk and Saylor=E2=80=99=
s initiative to make Bitcoin =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98greener=E2=80=99 bodes well =
for ESG narrative and institutional adoption,=E2=80=9D David Grider, strate=
gist at Fundstrat Global Advisors LLC, wrote in a note.At the same time, it=
 will take years for many of the largest miners to recalibrate where they s=
ource their energy.What does that mean? Well, consider that many=C2=A0big E=
SG funds invest in oil and gas companies. If you are interested in reducing=
 the climate impact of your investments and investing only in environmental=
ly sound companies, you can buy an ESG fund that buys=C2=A0the most environ=
mentally friendly oil companies.[1] And then your clients will say =E2=80=
=9Cwait doesn=E2=80=99t drilling for oil contribute to climate change=E2=80=
=9D and you will say =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s not the point, the point is th=
at the way these companies drill for oil is slightly better than the way th=
ose other companies drill for oil, and they have committed to become carbon=
-neutral=C2=A0in the far future.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0That is important, because, =
for various reasons (particularly: to track broad indexes with minimum erro=
r), big ESG-focused investors often want to buy oil companies. If you can f=
ind a way to buy oil companies and call it ESG, there=E2=80=99s a good busi=
ness there. And people have, and the way is:=09Make the environmental impac=
t of each oil company somehow legible and quantifiable.=09Focus on the oil =
companies that are relatively=C2=A0better on these legible metrics: They co=
ntribute less to climate change than their peers, or at least they are=C2=
=A0reducing=C2=A0their climate impact over time.=09Categorize oil companies=
 as=C2=A0a sector that every investor needs exposure to, so that ESG funds =
 can say =E2=80=9Cwe offer investors similar risk and returns that they wou=
ld achieve in broad market indexes while including the highest ESG-rated co=
mpanies in each sector.=E2=80=9DSimilarly here the trade is to make Bitcoin=
=E2=80=99s energy consumption and sources, and its climate impact, legible,=
 by =E2=80=9Cstandardizing energy reporting.=E2=80=9D Then you (Tesla, inst=
itutional investors, etc.) buy Bitcoin. And then when people complain about=
 Bitcoin=E2=80=99s environmental impact, now you have tools to reply. You c=
an say things like =E2=80=9Cyes but we enforce rigorous energy usage transp=
arency standards=C2=A0and only buy Bitcoins artisanally=C2=A0sourced from h=
ydroelectric plants,=E2=80=9D[2] or =E2=80=9Csure Bitcoin uses a lot of ene=
rgy but so does the S&P 500, and Bitcoin has reduced its use of coal power =
2.7% this year,=E2=80=9D[3] or whatever. You have transformed a vague and o=
minous problem =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cit seems like Bitcoin maybe uses a l=
ot of dirty electricity to make an abstract asset?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
into a peppy solution =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cour investment in Bitcoin is =
helping make it cleaner.=E2=80=9D The absolute problem persists =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0miners use a lot of electricity to mine Bitcoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0but yo=
u have turned the=C2=A0conversation to relative improvements in the problem=
.[4]Of course this only works=C2=A0if you accept the premise that Bitcoin i=
s an important asset class, that an investor should be finding the cleanest=
 way to buy Bitcoin rather than avoiding it altogether.[5] (=E2=80=9CYou al=
most never hear anyone complaining about how much electricity refrigerators=
 use,=E2=80=9D Joe Weisenthal wrote the=C2=A0other day, because everyone ac=
cepts that refrigeration is important.) If your policy is =E2=80=9Cwe inves=
t in every asset class in the most environmentally sensible way,=E2=80=9D a=
nd someone comes to you and says =E2=80=9Chey we have invented a new asset =
class, it is burning a ton of coal and keeping track of how much coal we=E2=
=80=99ve burned and paying each other for it,=E2=80=9D your initial inclina=
tion might be to say =E2=80=9Cwait that's not an asset class, that=E2=80=99=
s just burning coal, we don=E2=80=99t want any of that at all.=E2=80=9D But=
 once it=E2=80=99s worth a trillion dollars, sure, you have to figure out t=
he most environmentally friendly way to buy some.Bitcoin ETF-of-ETFsOne sim=
ple model of exchange-traded funds is that they are a way to invest without=
 paying taxes until you=E2=80=99re done investing. Here=E2=80=99s how regul=
ar traditional=C2=A0investing works:=09You have money that you don=E2=80=99=
