<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">The magical Elon money machine</h2><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">So obviously <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/23957730.264950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjQvYml0Y29pbi1ib3VuY2VzLWJhY2stYWJvdmUtMzctMDAwLWFmdGVyLXd=
lZWtlbmQtc2VsbG9mZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe2fef1e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this</a> is a story about <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23957730.264950/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMTcvZWxvbi1t=
dXNrLWNvbnRyb2xzLWJpdGNvaW4tYW5kLWRvZ2Vjb2luLXByaWNlcy13aXRoLXB1cmUtbWFnaWM=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB36b4c174" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> Elon Musk=E2=80=99s=C2=A0magic lamp</a> that mak=
es the price of Bitcoin go up and down:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Bitcoin traded lower on Tuesday as prices pulled back from a doubl=
e-digit percentage rally, stoked in part by Elon Musk=E2=80=99s effort to b=
olster the token=E2=80=99s green credentials on Twitter.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">The largest digital currency slipped as much as 6.5% to $36,4=
94 in New York, following a 16% jump on Monday. The wider Bloomberg Galaxy =
Crypto Index and tokens including Ether also dropped.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The Tesla Inc. CEO has roiled the token=E2=80=99s price this mon=
th, triggering a selloff by criticizing its energy profile and suspending B=
itcoin payments. Heightened regulatory rhetoric on cryptocurrencies from Ch=
ina also pressured the sector.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf =
the market continues to see wild swings based on Elon Musk tweets, it=E2=80=
=99s going to be a big set back for this asset class,=E2=80=9D said Matt Ma=
ley, chief market strategist for=C2=A0Miller Tabak + Co.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThe =
fact that it sees such wild swings to the tweets from one person takes away=
 the legitimacy of the asset class.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Fine, yes, in 2021 the main fact about Bitcoin is that Elon =
Musk decides whether its price goes up or down. Does that =E2=80=9Ctake awa=
y the legitimacy of the asset class=E2=80=9D? Man, look around; =E2=80=9Cle=
gitimacy=E2=80=9D is a weird thing to be worried about. I would say that it=
=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>interesting=C2=A0</em>to have a trillion-dollar asset c=
lass that is like =E2=80=9Cone guy will think of a number and your asset wi=
ll be worth that number.=E2=80=9D That really is a novel experiment in fina=
nce! I feel like we should give it some more time and see how it goes.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it strikes me that this is also a s=
tory about how environmental, social and governance (ESG) investing often w=
orks. In 2021 the other important fact about Bitcoin is that <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23957730.264950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjUvYml0Y29pbi1zLWJ0Yy1=
jb3N0LXRvLXNvY2lldHktaXMtaW1wb3NzaWJsZS10by1pZ25vcmU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB769e82a1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> miners use a lot of electricity to keep its ledger secure</a>, and this=
 fact has formed the pretext for a number of Musk=E2=80=99s recent tweets t=
elling the price to go up or down:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Pledges to make the industry more green have picked up since Musk=E2=80=
=99s criticisms. Several miners joined the Crypto Climate Accord, a private=
-sector initiative to decarbonize the crypto industry by 2030.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk and Michael Saylor, another long-time Bitcoin boo=
ster, tweeted Monday that they had held a call with major North American mi=
ners, including Michael Novogratz=E2=80=99s Galaxy Digital and publicly tra=
ded Hut 8 Mining Corp., to discuss =E2=80=9Cenergy usage transparency.=E2=
=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Saylor said the group agreed to form=
 the Bitcoin Mining Council =E2=80=9Cto standardize energy reporting.=E2=80=
=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk and Saylor=E2=80=99s initiative to=
 make Bitcoin =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98greener=E2=80=99 bodes well for ESG narrati=
ve and institutional adoption,=E2=80=9D David Grider, strategist at Fundstr=
at Global Advisors LLC, wrote in a note.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At=
 the same time, it will take years for many of the largest miners to recali=
brate where they source their energy.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">What does that mean? Well, consider that <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23957730.264950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTEtMTEvZXNnLXN0b2Nrcy1hcmUtZ3JhZGVkLW9=
uLWEtY3VydmU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB41d455ca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">many=C2=A0big ESG funds invest in oil=
 and gas companies</a>. If you are interested in reducing the climate impac=
t of your investments and investing only in environmentally sound companies=
, you can buy an ESG fund that buys=C2=A0<em>the most environmentally frien=
dly oil companies</em>.[1] And then your clients will say =E2=80=9Cwait doe=
sn=E2=80=99t drilling for oil contribute to climate change=E2=80=9D and you=
 will say =E2=80=9Cthat=E2=80=99s not the point, the point is that the way =
these companies drill for oil is slightly better than the way those other c=
ompanies drill for oil, and they have committed to become carbon-neutral=C2=
=A0in the far future.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That i=
s important, because, for various reasons (particularly: to track broad ind=
exes with minimum error), big ESG-focused investors often want to buy oil c=
ompanies. If you can find a way to buy oil companies and call it ESG, there=
=E2=80=99s a good business there. And people have, and the way is:</p><ol s=
tyle=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Make the environmental impact of each oil =
company somehow legible and quantifiable.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">Focus on the oil companies that are <em>relatively=C2=A0</em>better=
 on these legible metrics: They contribute less to climate change than thei=
r peers, or at least they are=C2=A0<em>reducing=C2=A0</em>their climate imp=
act over time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Categorize oil comp=
anies as=C2=A0a sector that every investor needs exposure to, so that ESG f=
unds <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23957730.2649=
50/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90b3AtZXNnLWZ1bmRzLWFyZS1hbGwtc3Rp=
bGwtaW52ZXN0ZWQtaW4tb2lsLWFuZC1nYXMtY29tcGFuaWVzLTExNTczNDY4MjAwP21vZD1ocF9=
sZWFkX3BvczE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa51b2194" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> can say</a> =E2=80=9Cwe offer invest=
ors similar risk and returns that they would achieve in broad market indexe=
s while including the highest ESG-rated companies in each sector.=E2=80=9D<=
/li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly here the trade is to make B=
itcoin=E2=80=99s energy consumption and sources, and its climate impact, le=
gible, by =E2=80=9Cstandardizing energy reporting.=E2=80=9D Then you (Tesla=
, institutional investors, etc.) buy Bitcoin. And then when people complain=
 about Bitcoin=E2=80=99s environmental impact, now you have tools to reply.=
 You can say things like =E2=80=9Cyes but we enforce rigorous energy usage =
transparency standards=C2=A0and only buy Bitcoins artisanally=C2=A0sourced =
from hydroelectric plants,=E2=80=9D[2] or =E2=80=9Csure Bitcoin uses a lot =
of energy but so does the S&amp;P 500, and Bitcoin has reduced its use of c=
oal power 2.7% this year,=E2=80=9D[3] or whatever. You have transformed a v=
ague and ominous problem =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cit seems like Bitcoin mayb=
e uses a lot of dirty electricity to make an abstract asset?=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0into a peppy solution =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cour investment in=
 Bitcoin is helping make it cleaner.=E2=80=9D The absolute problem persists=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0miners use a lot of electricity to mine Bitcoin =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but you have turned the=C2=A0<em>conversation </em>to relative improv=
ements in the problem.[4]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course this on=
ly works=C2=A0if you accept the premise that Bitcoin is an important asset =
class, that an investor should be finding the cleanest way to buy Bitcoin r=
ather than avoiding it altogether.[5] (=E2=80=9CYou almost never hear anyon=
e complaining about how much electricity refrigerators use,=E2=80=9D Joe We=
isenthal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23957730.=
264950/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9UaGVTdGFsd2FydC9zdGF0dXMvMTM5Njc4MTQ3NjQ2=
MTU1OTgxMQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbb3a41ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote the=C2=A0other day</a>, because e=
veryone accepts that refrigeration is important.) If your policy is =E2=80=
=9Cwe invest in every asset class in the most environmentally sensible way,=
=E2=80=9D and someone comes to you and says =E2=80=9Chey we have invented a=
 new asset class, it is burning a ton of coal and keeping track of how much=
 coal we=E2=80=99ve burned and paying each other for it,=E2=80=9D your init=
ial inclination might be to say =E2=80=9Cwait that's not an asset class, th=
at=E2=80=99s just burning coal, we don=E2=80=99t want any of that at all.=
=E2=80=9D But once it=E2=80=99s worth a trillion dollars, sure, you have to=
 figure out the most environmentally friendly way to buy some.</p><h2 style=
=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helveti=
ca, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; m=
argin-bottom: 0;">Bitcoin ETF-of-ETFs</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One =
simple model of exchange-traded funds is that they are a way to invest with=
out paying taxes until you=E2=80=99re done investing. Here=E2=80=99s how re=
gular traditional=C2=A0investing works:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: de=
cimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">You have money that you don=E2=80=99t need now but will need in 20 ye=
ars to pay for your kids=E2=80=99 college or whatever.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">You buy some assets.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">You change the assets from time to time: Some things go up and you =
sell them, or buy more; other things go down and you sell them, or buy more=
. You have a target allocation of X% to Thing A and Y% to Thing B and Z% to=
 Thing C, but=C2=A0if Thing A goes up a lot compared to Things B and C then=
 you will have more than X% of it and you=E2=80=99ll have to sell some. Als=
o over time your target allocations might change, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Every time you sell an asset for a profit, you pay tax=
es on the gains.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In 20 years you s=
ell all of the assets, pay taxes on whatever gains you haven=E2=80=99t alre=
ady paid taxes on, and use the money to pay for=C2=A0college or whatever.</=
li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Step 4 is the bummer here: You keep pa=
ying taxes along the way, because you have taxable gains. It might=C2=A0<em=
>feel</em>, to you, like you don=E2=80=99t: From your perspective, you put =
in money in=C2=A0Step 1 and take it out in Step 5, and you only get to enjo=
y the gains in Step 5; any gains in Steps 3 and 4 are just part of the inve=
sting process, not income that you were planning to spend. But the tax law =
says that if you sell an asset for a gain you pay taxes on it, even if you =
are planning to reinvest and aren=E2=80=99t ready to pay for college or wha=
tever yet.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you invest via mutual funds, =
instead of by buying stocks and bonds directly, the process is the same. In=
 fact in some ways mutual funds are worse because=C2=A0they=C2=A0buy=C2=A0a=
nd sell=C2=A0stocks and bonds over time, not just to rebalance their portfo=
lios but also to deal with redemptions by other investors, and their sales =
can incur taxes that you have to pay.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>If you invest via ETFs, though, it=E2=80=99s different.=C2=A0U.S. tax law=
=C2=A0allows ETFs to adjust their holdings without incurring any taxes. (Th=
is oversimplifies. We talked more about the mechanisms in the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23957730.264950/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMjkvZGVhbHMtb24tdGhlLX=
RyYWluLWFyZS1ldmVyeW9uZS1zLWJ1c2luZXNz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB95be55db" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> =E2=80=9CH=
eartbeats=E2=80=9D section here</a>; they involve =E2=80=9Cauthorized parti=
cipants=E2=80=9D doing in-kind trades where they exchange the underlying as=
sets for shares of the ETF in tax-exempt transactions.) So the way an ETF w=
orks is roughly:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40=
px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have money th=
at you don=E2=80=99t need now but will need in 20 years to pay for your kid=
s=E2=80=99 college or whatever.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Yo=
u buy shares in an=C2=A0ETF, which holds some underlying assets.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The ETF changes the assets that it holds fro=
m time to time.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But you don=E2=80=
=99t pay taxes when that happens.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
In 20 years you sell your ETF shares, pay taxes on any gains (what your ETF=
 shares are worth minus what you paid for them), and use the money to pay f=
or college or whatever.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is much =
neater. You pay taxes only at the end, when you have gains you can enjoy. I=
 am somewhat exaggerating the benefits here, because most ETFs are specific=
 to some asset class or sector. So you might buy a Stocks ETF and a Bonds E=
TF, and as stocks go up you will sell some of the Stocks ETF and buy more o=
f the Bonds ETF, and that will incur taxes just as if you=E2=80=99d sold so=
me stocks and bought some bonds. (On the other hand the Stocks ETF can get =
rid of some stocks and add other stocks=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>incurrin=
g taxes.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in principle you could have a=
n ETF that is like the=C2=A0Everything You=E2=80=99ll Ever Need ETF, and it=
 does all of the rebalancing for you, without you ever paying taxes until y=
ou sell. In practice, you probably won=E2=80=99t find exactly the Everythin=
g You Specifically Will Ever Need to Pay for College in 20 Years ETF, but t=
here are Giving You Some Target Allocation to Stocks and Bonds and Rebalanc=
ing Periodically ETFs that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
